properties.name: New Ground (online only)
properties.description: 25 homes designed with the Older Women’s Co-Housing group using PTE’s ‘fabric first’ approach which maximises the benefits of orientation, air-tightness and insulation and following the co-housing model.

properties.name: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre
properties.description: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre, at Hornchurch Country Park, the Former RAF Hornchurch Airfield.

properties.name: Devonport Mausoleum
properties.description: Beautiful mausoleum in former Royal Navy cemetery, restored 1999 by the University of Greenwich. Many interesting plaques and grave stones.

properties.name: Dorich House Museum
properties.description: The former studio home of the sculptor Dora Gordine and her husband the Hon. Richard Hare, a scholar of Russian art and literature. 1930s house over four floors including a flat roof terrace and views of Richmond Park.

properties.name: Drapers' Hall
properties.description: Livery hall first built in the 1530s, twice destroyed by fire and rebuilt (1666 & 1772). Late 19C facade and opulent Victorian interior.

properties.name: Dulwich Picture Gallery
properties.description: Britain's oldest purpose-built public art gallery. At the centre of this seminal building Soane designed a mysterious mausoleum for the gallery's founders. Recent glass, bronze and brick extension. RIBA Award Winner.

properties.name: The Old Finsbury Town Hall
properties.description: Opened by Lord Rosebery, an ornate building with elegant decor influenced by the Art Nouveau movement. Several notable rooms including the Great Hall with unique stained glass, antique mirrors and Clerkenwell Angel statuettes.

properties.name: Freemasons' Hall
properties.description: Monumental Art Deco exterior belying elaborate and varied interior decoration: extensive use of mosaic, stained glass, decorated ceilings and lighting.

properties.name: Winchmore Hill Friends Meeting House & Burial Ground
properties.description: Grade II listed, built 1790. A central double door under a bracketed cornice hood, large sash windows with delicate glazing bars. Panelled interior. Curved entrance wall allowed carriages to turn in the narrow lane. Notable burial ground.

properties.name: King's Cross Public Realm
properties.description: King's Cross is a 67 acre development in Central London being transformed into a new city quarter with 20 regenerated heritage buildings, new homes, offices, public spaces, shops, galleries, bars, restaurants, schools and a university.

properties.name: Greenwich Yacht Club
properties.description: Contemporary timber and aluminium building using existing pier, offering unique views of the river, the O2 and the Thames Barrier.

properties.name: Hammersmith Library
properties.description: Fine Carnegie-funded Edwardian library (1905). First floor Ionic colonnade flanked by end pavilions, large Baroque doorway, and glazed barrel-vaults. 16/17C stained and painted Dutch glass  and statues of Shakespeare and Milton on exterior.

properties.name: Barking Riverside London
properties.description: A new sustainable neighbourhood being created alongside 2km of south-facing Thames river frontage. A partnership with The Mayor of London and L&Q, 10,800 new homes will house up to 29,000 people.

properties.name: Highgate School Chapel, Library, Museum
properties.description: Highgate is three schools in one. Founded by Sir Roger Cholmeley, Lord Chief Justice of England, in 1565, Highgate is governed as a single charitable foundation.

properties.name: HM Treasury
properties.description: Online only. A quadrangular, English Baroque revival building. Grade II* listed government office covering the entire complex, Great George Street constructed 1899-17 in two phases. Refurbishment completed 2002, now occupied by HM Treasury

properties.name: Hogarth's House
properties.description: Early 18C red brick home of artist William Hogarth extended significantly c1749-1764. A 2020 extension adds a curved glass wall in the shape of Hogarth's Line of Beauty. Delightful walled garden containing famous ancient mulberry tree.

properties.name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square
properties.description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass and bold sacred sculpture at what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake and Christopher Whall.

properties.name: The Hurlingham Club
properties.description: Bordering the Thames in Fulham, this 18th Century Georgian-style clubhouse is set in 42 acres of magnificent grounds. One of Britain’s greatest private members’ clubs, it retains its quintessentially English traditions and heritage.

properties.name: Isokon Building (Lawn Road Flats)
properties.description: Grade I listed 1934 residential block of flats in Hampstead, designed by the Canadian modernist architect Wells Coates for clients Jack and Molly Pritchard. English Heritage blue plaque for Bauhaus masters Gropius, Breuer and Moholy-Nagy.

properties.name: Kingston Library, Museum and Art Gallery
properties.description: Adjoining Grade II listed Carnegie-funded library, museum and art gallery. Museum holdings range from ceramics to topographical drawings, including the collection left by Eadweard Muybridge, a native of Kingston and photographic pioneer.

properties.name: Abbey Mills Pumping Station
properties.description: Abbey Mills pumping station 'A', built by engineer Joseph Bazalgette, Edmund Cooper and architect Charles Driver. Built between 1865 and 1868 it has been described as the cathedral of sewage.

properties.name: London Museum of Water & Steam
properties.description: The Museum is housed within in a unique collection of Grade I and II listed buildings. Even though they were purpose-built and purely functional buildings, the architect took great care to make the buildings aesthetically pleasing.

properties.name: St Martin's Parish Church, West Drayton
properties.description:
A Grade II* listed church dating from 13th century with some interesting features
Adjacent to a 16th century Gate House

properties.name: King George V Pumping Station
properties.description: Designed to pump water from the River Lee into the King George V reservoir, the building houses three old disused gas Humphrey pumps, and two electric pumps currently in service.

properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - King William Court
properties.description: Wren-designed building completed under the direction of Hawksmoor and Vanbrugh, 1698-1712. Original wood panelling, refurbished by Dannatt Johnson in 2001 for University of Greenwich.

properties.name: Kingswood House  (online only)
properties.description: Grade II listed building. Substantial villa built in form of stone-faced baronial castle for the inventor of Bovril. Now contains a library and community centre.

properties.name: Lamorbey House
properties.description: World-renowned Rose Bruford drama college with recent additions and landscaping to provide contemporary state of the art facilities. Site also includes Grade II listed Lamorbey Park Mansion – a rare survivor of Sidcup's Georgian houses.

properties.name: The Swedenborg Society
properties.description: Grade II listed Georgian domestic building c1760, formerly part of Bedford Estate. Interior refurbished 1924-5 to form lecture hall (restored 2014), library, bookshop and offices. Oak woodwork and green Doulton tiles line the staircase.

properties.name: Calouste Gulbenkian Foundation
properties.description: The Foundation's artistic and social interests are at the heart of the design. A dramatic intervention to the first floor allows natural light to permeate to the ground floor.

properties.name: Walthamstow Pumphouse Museum
properties.description: Grade II listed Victorian engine house remodelled to take a pair of 1895 Marshall steam engines, still in working order. A museum celebrating the rich Boroughs and the Lea Valley Region Industrial Heritage.

properties.name: Bow Church – St Mary
properties.description: Medieval village church, restored in late 19C and after bomb damage in WWII. 15C font and memorials from five centuries. Grade II* listed. Refurbished for 700th anniversary in 2011; the bell tower and cupola were restored in 2017-18.

properties.name: Manor House Gardens Ice House
properties.description: Grade II listed ice well and underground chambers (1770) in Manor House Gardens park, which provided ice for nearby Manor House. Cited in 2002 Civic Trust Awards.

properties.name: Markfield Beam Engine and House
properties.description:
A masterpiece of Victorian engineering, Markfield Beam Engine provided a vital public health facility from 1855-1964. 

Steaming demonstrations, 4 & 5 Sept from 12.30pm.

Set in Markfield Park along side the River Lee.

properties.name: Myddelton House
properties.description: Former home of the great horticulturist Edward Augustus Bowles. Neoclassical yellow Suffolk stock brick villa. Victorian conservatory to south side. Mid-19C extension to north end. Adam style ceilings to ground floor.

properties.name: Oak Room, New River Head
properties.description: Formerly boardroom of the 17C water house, the Oak Room is a fine late Renaissance room demonstrating the New River Company's wealth. 1697 carved oak interior, attributed to Grinling Gibbons, including overmantel and panels over the doors.

properties.name: Museum of London
properties.description: Part of an ambitious redevelopment of the area following WWll bombing, this building forms part of the Barbican complex. The architects were inspired by post-war modernism to include green design elements and raised walkways.

properties.name: Nunhead Cemetery
properties.description: Magnificent Victorian cemetery with Gothic chapel & restored & ruined lodge. One of London's wildest cemeteries. Part restored with the help of a lottery grant. 52 acres of woodland, with bats, owls, foxes & squirrels. Grade II* landscape.

properties.name: Orleans House Gallery
properties.description: Louis Philippe, Duc d'Orleans, lived here between 1815-17. Gibbs' Baroque Octagon Room and adjoining gallery/19C stable block are the remaining parts of Orleans House. The Octagon Room was restored in 2018. Contemporary art gallery.

properties.name: Royal Over-Seas League
properties.description: Over-Seas House is an amalgamation of two Grade I listed buildings – Rutland House (James Gibbs, 1736) and Vernon House (1835 rebuilt 1905), with an Art Deco style wing added in 1937.

properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - Admiral's House, Jacobean Undercroft, talks in the grounds and Smartphone tour
properties.description: Sir Christopher Wren's riverside masterpiece in Greenwich, built as the Royal Hospital for Seamen and begun in 1696.

properties.name: Paxton Locher House
properties.description: A unique modern courtyard house making brilliant use of a restricted site. A retractable glass roof gives wonderful natural light and opens the house to the sky in dry weather.

properties.name: St Paul's Bow Common
properties.description: Described as 'the most significant church built after the WWII in Britain' - Brutalist, inclusive and influential signpost for future church design.

properties.name: Pitzhanger Manor & Gallery
properties.description: Designed by Sir John Soane as a family home and country residence. Following a three-year conservation project,  Pitzhanger has been returned to Soane’s innovative original design and re-opened to the public in March 2019.

properties.name: Pope's Grotto
properties.description: Grotto with mineral decoration is last remaining part of Alexander Pope's villa built 1720. The villa was demolished 1808 and replaced and redeveloped many times in following years but Pope's Grotto remains.

properties.name: The Old Town Hall, Richmond
properties.description: Red brick and Bath stone grand 'Elizabethan Renaissance' style building altered by war, political changes and reflecting Richmond's history. Overlooking the war memorial and the Thames.

properties.name: Guildhall Art Gallery
properties.description: Houses the City of London's art collection, built over remains of London's 2C Roman amphitheatre. Façade uses Portland stone and Collyweston stone slates. Interior uses finishes of marble, American elm, damask and painted wall coverings.

properties.name: Queen Elizabeth II Stadium
properties.description: 2-storey concrete sports pavilion in streamlined 1930s style. Building work interrupted by WW2 and completed in 1952. Distinctive 'drum' contains stylised staircase leading to glass-walled café and sheltered seating.

properties.name: Queen Mary  University of London, Mile End Campus
properties.description: Explore the hidden corners of Queen Mary University's Mile End campus with Professor Nadia Valman, an expert in the history and culture of east London.

properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Mary Court
properties.description: Last major building on the site (1751). Original layout, timber panelling, barrel vaulting and Portland stone. Refurbished in 2000 by Dannatt Johnson for University of Greenwich.

properties.name: Reform Club
properties.description: Built as a Whig gentleman's club and inspired by Italian Renaissance palaces. Lobby leads to an enclosed colonnaded courtyard with complementary glazed roof and tessellated floor. Tunnelled staircase leads to upper floor.

properties.name: RIBA
properties.description: Fine example of Grade II* listed 1930s architecture with many original features and fittings and home to the world-class British Architectural Library collections. Open for pre-book visits only.

properties.name: St Alban Church
properties.description: Notable 1930s Grade II listed church with Swedish and German influences externally. Landmark tower. Stepped tunnel-vault with arches to side aisle walls giving a light lively interior. Marquetry panelling to Lady Chapel.

properties.name: Royal Hospital Chelsea, home of the Chelsea Pensioners
properties.description: Numbered amongst the UK's architectural glories and boasting 66 acres of beautiful grounds, the Royal Hospital Chelsea has been home to the iconic Army veteran community fondly known as the 'Chelsea Pensioners' since its foundation in 1692.

properties.name: Royal Opera House
properties.description: Housing the Royal Opera and the Royal Ballet, the historic building was reconfigured in 2018 by Stanton Williams to deliver not only world-class performance spaces, but also a welcoming and inclusive cultural and social hub.

properties.name: Senate House
properties.description: London’s tallest secular building when it opened as the HQ of the University of London and home to the Ministry of Information during WWII, this Grade II* listed landmark features Classicism and Art Deco elements.

properties.name: BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir
properties.description: Europe’s first traditional Hindu temple is a masterpiece of exquisite Indian craftsmanship. Using 5,000 tonnes of Italian and Indian marble and the finest Bulgarian limestone, it was hand-carved in India before being assembled in London.

properties.name: Bunhill Heat and Power Energy Centre
properties.description: A district heating energy centre providing low carbon heating to around 1,300 properties.

properties.name: St Paul's Cathedral - Triforium Tour
properties.description: Guided tours of the Triforium space to see: items from the cathedral collections including Christopher Wren’s magnificent ‘Great Model’ made in 1673; the Geometrical Staircase and the stunning view from the West Gallery.

properties.name: South London Gallery
properties.description: Public contemporary art gallery housed in 3 listed Victorian buildings restored by 6a architects. Comprising galleries, café, shop, gardens, kitchen and converted Victorian Fire Station.

properties.name: St Augustine's Tower
properties.description: Grade I listed, remaining tower of medieval parish church, with working late 16C clock. New exhibition of Hackney's history. Extensive views from roof. (Organised by Hackney Historic Buildings Trust).

properties.name: Peter Jones
properties.description: Grade II* listed building, involving complex mix of new build and restoration. Britain's first ever curtain walling and listed features such as spiral staircase. Sloane Room has one of best views over Chelsea. RIBA Award Winner 2005.

properties.name: The City Churches: St Mary Aldermary
properties.description:
Guild Church, first mentioned c1080. Oldest of the City churches dedicated to St Mary. Only Wren church built after the Great Fire, courtesy of a bequest, in late Gothic style.  
Please wear masks and use the hand sanitizer at the door.

properties.name: St Mary's Convent
properties.description: Convent in 18C Grade II listed house, c1764-1792, with original features including fine decorative plasterwork. Various additions including west wing (1913-15), and harmonious care home facilities and chapel by PRP Architects (1998-2001).

properties.name: St Peter & St Paul Harlington
properties.description: Grade I listed church dating from 1086, with Norman font and Norman stone arch, carved with cats heads. Interesting monuments including Easter sepulchre, ancient yew tree in churchyard. Good restoration between 1830 and 1860.

properties.name: The City Churches: St Stephen Walbrook
properties.description: Wren's own and 'finest City Church'.  Fantastic architecture with different shapes,  twelve Corinthian columns and covered by huge dome - first of its type. Central stone altar by Henry Moore installed in 1987. Birthplace of the Samaritans.

properties.name: Swakeleys Estate
properties.description: A most important house in Ickenham an outstanding example of Jacobean architecture built in the 1630s. Red brick construction laid in English bond on an H plan. Great Hall includes the 1655 Harrington Screen, 18C marble fireplace panelling.

properties.name: The Art Workers' Guild
properties.description: 1713 terraced house with 1914 hall at rear. Notable renovated Arts and Crafts interior. Newly refurbished glass vaulted courtyard. Portraits of Guild Masters since 1884.

properties.name: British Library
properties.description: Highly acclaimed building of red brick with colourful window details and roof, the British Library is the ultimate in post-modernity. The design follows the English Free Style of architecture. RIBA Award Winner.

properties.name: The Great Barn, Harmondsworth
properties.description: The timbers of this great medieval barn (1426-7), over 190 feet long and nearly 40 feet high, are 95% original. Displays include the conservation/repairs carried out in 2014 and its place in the agricultural history of the village.

properties.name: The Hospital Chapel of St Mary & St Thomas
properties.description: Founded c1145 by the Abbess of Barking as a hospice for thirteen old and infirm men, the present building is 12C and 19C. Grade II* listed with many interesting monuments, including Burne-Jones windows.

properties.name: The Ismaili Centre
properties.description: Part of an international family of Ismaili Centres, a religious, cultural and social space for the Shia Ismaili Muslim community. The serenity of the entrance fountain to the roof garden reflects Muslim traditions in architecture and design

properties.name: The Royal Society
properties.description: A spectacular Grade I listed building designed by famed architect John Nash. Built in 1831, these former townhouses have undergone refurbishments throughout their history. The building is now home to the UK's national science academy.

properties.name: The Stanley Picker Trust, Picker House (online only)
properties.description: Completed in 1968 by Kenneth Wood, RIBA, T Eng (CEI).  A time capsule of the 1960s, it is set in a quiet cul-de-sac on steeply sloping ground which both inspired and challenged the architect when creating the modern split-level design.

properties.name: The Temple Wanstead Park
properties.description: The Temple, 1760 remnant of magnificent Wanstead House estate, set in Grade II listed landscape Wanstead Park. Displays within, activities for all under Doric portico & in grassed enclosure.

properties.name: Tooting Bec Lido
properties.description: Outdoor pool 100x33 yards. One million gallons of unheated water. Iconic outdoor cubicle doors, fountain and café added in the 1930s, with Art Deco style entrance in 2001. Sports hall pavilion added in 2016.

properties.name: Trinity Buoy Wharf/Container City
properties.description: Home to London's only lighthouse, fine stock buildings and examples of the innovative Container City buildings. This former buoy manufacturing site is now a centre for the creative industries with various sculptures and installations.

properties.name: Union Chapel
properties.description: Online only. An architectural Grade I treasure that’s home to an inclusive church, an award winning venue, a unique organ and The Margins Project for those homeless and in crisis in London.

properties.name: Valence House
properties.description: Grade II* listed 15C and later manor house with medieval moat. Recently discovered late 16C wall painting and impressive oak paneling. Evocative museum galleries that bring Barking & Dagenham's past alive.

properties.name: The Church of Our Most Holy Redeemer
properties.description: A unique II* listed Italianate church by John Dando Sedding with attached Campanile and Institute Building. Of particular significance in the church is the imposing baldacchino over the High Altar, which dominates the east end.

properties.name: Hampstead Garden Suburb Free Church
properties.description: Grade I listed Non-conformist church, set in the suburb's integrally planned Central Square to balance St Jude's Church nearby, but with a low concrete dome. Distinctive interior with large Tuscan columns on high brick plinths.

properties.name: West India Dock Impounding Station
properties.description: The recently automated impounding station controls the water level in the docks using the original Worthington Simpson pumps driven by Lancashire dynamo.

properties.name: City of Westminster Archives Centre
properties.description: Modern red brick building purpose-built to house the City of Westminster's historic records. Opportunity to visit the conservation studio and see treasures of the archives.

properties.name: Benjamin Franklin House
properties.description: Grade I listed Georgian house, the only surviving home of Benjamin Franklin, retaining many original features including central staircase, lathing, 18th Century panelling, stoves, windows, fittings and beams.

properties.name: Whitewebbs Museum of Transport
properties.description:
Victorian Pumping station built for the New River Company. When 
 converted to a museum the well, original iron roof bracing, hand operated crane,  weighbridge and many of the splendid Victorian details of the design were retained.

properties.name: Hanwell Flight of Locks & Three Bridges
properties.description: Flight of locks and side ponds at Hanwell is a Scheduled  Monument. Three Bridges is a unique stacked intersection of road, rail and canal and Brunel's last major railway project. Walks led by knowledgeable enthusiasts.

properties.name: All Saints Church, Edmonton
properties.description: Church dating back to at least early C12. Charles and Mary Lamb are buried in the churchyard.

properties.name: Christ Church
properties.description: Grade II* listed church with ragstone tower, spire, good stained glass by Kempe and recently restored William Hill organ. A characteristic work of Scott. It is Gothic Revival in the style of the 13C.

properties.name: Christ Church, Streatham
properties.description: Grade I listed pioneering brick polychromy. Designed with early Christian, Italian, Ottoman, Alhambran, Mamluk, Sevillean and Ancient Egyptian influences with fine mosaics and stained glass by Crane, Bentley. Lee and Hayward.

properties.name: Parish Church of St Andrew Enfield
properties.description: Listed church, much added to, with a recently refurbished organ which has a fine circa 1750s wooden organ case. There are many fine memorials. The Church has an eight-bell peal – the oldest bell dates from 1680.

properties.name: St Andrew's Kingsbury (new church)
properties.description: Meticulous 1930s rebuilding (complete with original furnishings) of an 1840s Marylebone church. Grade I listed. Contains works by Pugin, Burges, Street, Pearson and Butterfield.

properties.name: St Barnabas Church
properties.description: Early English style, full of Pre-Raphaelite decoration. Important works by Bodley, Comper and Cundy and windows by Kempe and Tower. First Oxford Movement church. Recently restored 10 bell peal; bell ringing quarter peal once a month

properties.name: Bells and Belfries at St Botolph Aldgate
properties.description:
Opportunity to hear a description and watch a demonstration of bell ringing (on Saturday only).
Church built by architect of Mansion House and contains London's oldest organ.

properties.name: St Dunstan and All Saints Church
properties.description: Grade I listed early medieval parish church (from 952 before Tower of London) in spacious churchyard. Fine interior: Anglo-Saxon Rood, Norman font, 'squint', fine memorials incl founders of Trinity House, 1950s glass. Bells of Stepney.

properties.name: St James the Less Church
properties.description: One of London's best Victorian churches and a key building in the history of the Gothic Revival. Polychromatic brickwork, with internal art work by G.F. Watts and Thomas Earp, windows and painted ceiling by Clayton and Bell. Grade I listed.

properties.name: St John the Baptist Holland Road
properties.description: Possibly the last stone-vaulted building built in London – of soaring nobility embellished with carvings and fittings of exceptional quality.

properties.name: St Mary Magdalene Church & Nature Reserve
properties.description: Grade I listed 12C church, with London's largest churchyard and one of the best-preserved Norman archways in the country, as well as other interesting features, including an anchorite's cell and 750-year-old wall paintings.

properties.name: Grand Junction at St Mary Magdalene Church, Paddington
properties.description: Grade I Victorian Gothic church by G E Street, architect of the Royal Courts of Justice. The recent conservation project reveals the majestic colours of Daniel Bell's painted ceiling, plus Dow Jones Architects' contemporary heritage wing.

properties.name: St Mary the Virgin
properties.description: Small Grade I listed 12C chapel in lovely churchyard setting, it retains original architectural features and has interesting brasses, monuments and stained glass windows.

properties.name: St Mary's Church, Battersea
properties.description: Classic Grade I listed Georgian church with outstanding interior and monuments. Renovated 2019/20.

properties.name: St Paul's, Newington
properties.description: Modern architecture church with large copper and lead roof and concrete, brick and stained glass external structure. Marble, wood and plaster interior and artwork by Sculptor Freda Pinto and Gerald Holtom.

properties.name: Brentham Garden Suburb
properties.description: Britain's first co-partnership garden suburb, first houses built 1901. Parker and Unwin's plan introduced 1907, mainly Arts and Crafts style; fascinating social history.

properties.name: Tower Hamlets Cemetery Park
properties.description: One of the magnificent 7 cemeteries. Burials ceased 1966, now 31 acres of woodland, meadows & ponds including the Soanes Centre (Robson Kelly 1993). Of outstanding importance for flora and fauna, set amongst funereal monuments, some listed

properties.name: All Saints, Foots Cray
properties.description: Medieval church (c1330) amended 1863 by Hakewill and retaining original elements such as windows and an arch to the north aisle, and altar tomb of Sir Simon de Vaughan.

properties.name: Brentford & Isleworth Quaker Meeting House
properties.description: Grade II* listed late-Georgian Quaker Meeting House (1785) set in garden with burial ground. Meeting room has wood panelling, elders' bench, upper gallery with drop shutters, and fine brickwork detailing. Contemporary brick boundary wall.

properties.name: Bruce Castle Museum
properties.description: Tudor Manor House built for Sir William Compton in 1514, substantially altered in 17C, 18C & 19C. A museum since 1906 housing local history and community collections, archives, art & exhibitions of Bruce Castle, and Haringey area.

properties.name: 10 Downing Street
properties.description: 10 Downing Street has been the residence of British Prime Ministers since 1735. Behind its famous black door the most important decisions affecting Britain for the last 284 years have been taken.

properties.name: Caledonian Park: Clock Tower Tours
properties.description: Opened in 1855 as centrepiece of the Metropolitan Cattle Market. The clock tower offers magnificent views over London. The clock mechanism was made by John Moore of Clerkenwell. The tower has been renovated with help from the Heritage Fund.

properties.name: Canada House
properties.description: Canada's diplomatic home in the United Kingdom, the revitalised Canada House serves as a showcase for the very best of Canadian art and design in the 21C.

properties.name: The Charterhouse
properties.description: Founded as a Black Death burial ground, the site has served as a Carthusian monastery, Tudor mansion, school and an almshouse, which it remains to this day. The Charterhouse opened to the public in 2017 with a new museum.

properties.name: St George's Bloomsbury
properties.description: St George's Bloomsbury is one of the twelve new churches designed and paid for under the 1711 Act of Parliament for building fifty new Churches, and the sixth and final London Church designed by Hawksmoor.

properties.name: City Hall
properties.description: Home of the Mayor of London and London Assembly, an environmentally-aware building with innovative spiral ramp and fine views across London.

properties.name: Coombe Conduit
properties.description: Coombe Conduit is one of Kingston’s most important ancient monuments. It was built around 1540 as part of a system to collect fresh water from springs on Kingston Hill and channel it to  Hampton Court Palace.

properties.name: All Saints Church (The Old Church)
properties.description:
Original parish church of Chingford, with Norman foundations and interesting monuments.
Tudor porch.

properties.name: St Peter-in-the-Forest Church & Community Centre
properties.description: An 'Italian Romanesque' church set in Epping Forest, St Peter's was founded in 1840 and extended in 1887. The building underwent a major reordering throughout 2020 to save it from subsidence and create new community facilities.

properties.name: Centre of the Cell and Neuron Pod, Queen Mary University of London
properties.description: Neuron Pod is a striking 23-metre long and 10-metre high free-standing structure – designed as an extension to Centre of the Cell, an informal science learning centre at Queen Mary University of London’s Whitechapel campus.

properties.name: St John the Divine
properties.description: St John’s has a wide nave approached via a narthex formed under the gallery running the width of the west end.  East of the nave is a chancel flanked to the south by the Lady Chapel and to the north by the organ chamber with loft over.

properties.name: Garden Court Chambers
properties.description: Inigo Jones design 1640 at 59/60 LIF, copied  by 57/58  with portico and elliptical staircase added by Soane.  Refurbished by current occupiers, a barristers' chambers. Retains many original features, staircases, fireplaces and mouldings

properties.name: Westminster Quaker Meeting House
properties.description: Opened in 1883, with front doors added in the 1920s. It was bomb-damaged in 1941 and rebuilt in 1956. Grade II listed registered place of worship, it contains a peaceful meeting room and 1950s wood panelling and fittings.

properties.name: Baitul Futuh Mosque
properties.description: Largest purpose-built mosque in Western Europe accommodating 13,000 worshippers. The building is a blend of Islamic and modern British architecture and incorporates much of the structure of an old dairy site.

properties.name: St Pancras Church & Crypt
properties.description: Unique Greek-style parish church. Grade I listed building inspired by the ionic temple of the Erechtheum on the Acropolis. A notable feature are the Caryatids guarding the entrances to the crypt.

properties.name: New Scotland Yard
properties.description: The Met Police’s home on the Embankment, created from the 1930s Curtis Green building with a new curved glass pavilion entrance and extensions to the rooftop and rear. Winner of the 2017 Prime Minister’s Better Public Building Award.

properties.name: Whitehall Historic House
properties.description: Originally a farmer's house dating to 1500, with jettied upper storey. Later additions reflect the changing lifestyles of the owners, including the Killicks for over two centuries. Now houses scale model of Henry VIII's Nonsuch Palace.

properties.name: Little Holland House (online only)
properties.description: Closed for refurbishment. Grade II listed building inspired by the ideals of John Ruskin and William Morris and contains Dickinson's paintings, hand-made furniture, furnishings, metalwork and friezes, in Arts & Crafts style.

properties.name: Carshalton Water Tower and Historic Gardens
properties.description: Early 18C Grade II listed building incorporating plunge bath with Delft tiles, orangery, saloon and pump chamber with part-restored water wheel. Hermitage and sham bridge in grounds.

properties.name: All Saints Carshalton
properties.description: 12C south aisle and former chancel. Blomfield nave, chancel, baptistry. Kempe glass, Bodley reredos and screen, spectacular Comper decorations, monuments and brasses, award-winning lighting scheme, fine modern benches.

properties.name: Thames Chase Forest Centre
properties.description: Distinctive award-winning visitor centre of modern timber sustainable construction forming an A-frame building roofed with cedar shingles, attached to 17C listed barn - one of the best preserved in the London area.

properties.name: The City Churches: St Mary-le-Bow
properties.description: Founded by William the Conqueror's Archbishop Lanfranc in 1080 (the significant crypt survives) St Mary-le-Bow was rebuilt, notably by Wren after the Great Fire and by Laurence King in 1964 after WWII destruction. Home of Bow Bells.

properties.name: Honeywood Museum
properties.description: Chalk and flint house dating to 17C with additions including extensions of 1896 and 1903 when owned by John Pattinson Kirk. Rich in period detail and the interior restored and stairs opened up with funding from the Heritage Lottery Fund.

properties.name: City Information Centre
properties.description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. This subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's. RIBA Award Winner 2009.

properties.name: Pushkin House
properties.description: A centre of Russian culture in London, this Grade II* listed Georgian townhouse has a fine staircase which has been meticulously restored, and a large reception room for music salons.

properties.name: Working Men's College
properties.description: Outstanding Edwardian building (1905 grade II; many original features). The oldest UK adult college, founded 1854 by FD Maurice, John Ruskin & Christian Socialists. Purpose-designed by WD Caroe; updated for modern educational aspirations.

properties.name: Hermitage Community Moorings
properties.description: A development of residential and recreational moorings for historic vessels on the Thames. The unique Pier House, built to a high specification, provides a floating community centre just downstream from Tower Bridge.

properties.name: Eco House
properties.description:
ONLINE ONLY.

A Georgian fronted terrace house, remodelled in 2016 to create an 'L' shaped modern eco house. Open and private living spaces designed horizontally across the ground floor, quiet relaxation spaces designed vertically.

properties.name: A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage
properties.description: Ruskinian walk from RIBA award-winning Chiswick Business Park, Gunnersbury Triangle Nature Reserve through South Acton Estate, birthplace of artist Patrick Caulfield; Woodlands Park Ice House; to home of Wm Willett, of Daylight Saving Time

properties.name: Two Temple Place
properties.description: By gothic revivalist architect, John Loughborough Pearson, and completed in 1895 for William Waldorf Astor as his estate office, the building overlooks the River Thames and embodies the outstanding workmanship of the late Victorian period.

properties.name: Skinner-Trevino House
properties.description: A late Victorian house which has been almost completely gutted; now flooded with light by a new glass extension opening onto the semi-open plan ground level and a glass box extension into the roof.

properties.name: St Bernard's Houses
properties.description: 21 houses, in 3 terraces, built by Swiss architects Atelier 5 for Wates. Living areas on the upper floor are approached through a garden court. Bedrooms downstairs open to a lower garden. Pevsner wrote, 'a group with few equals in Britain'.

properties.name: Gresham College - Barnard's Inn Hall
properties.description: Barnard's Inn dates back to the mid 13C. The hall contains three wooden bays dating from 15C with later linenfold wood panelling added in 1525. It was the Mercers' School and today is home to Gresham College offering FREE lectures for all.

properties.name: Havering Museum
properties.description: A cultural centre in part of the old Romford Brewery building near to the historic market place. Permanent and temporary exhibition displays tell the story of the London Borough of Havering from Bronze Age to present day.

properties.name: Meridian Water Masterplan Tour
properties.description: A unique site in the borough of Enfield. Meridian Water will be a distinctive neighbourhood designed to nurture economic, environmental and social sustainability. The tour provides an insight to the soon to be bold and unique development.

properties.name: Dalston Eastern Curve Garden
properties.description: A vital community garden offering a model for maximum good for communities and for the environment on a small urban plot. It is now a site of Local Importance for Nature Conservation. Shortlisted for the Open City Stewardship Awards 2021.

properties.name: Arcola Outside (Arcola Theatre)
properties.description: Arcola Outside is a brand-new outdoor performance space and bar in the heart of Dalston, designed by multi-award-winning stage designer Jon Bausor. A flexible, multi-purpose space, for live performances, screenings, installations and more.

properties.name: Christ Church Southgate and the Minchenden Oak Garden
properties.description: Grade II listed church with fine collection of Pre-Raphaelite stained glass windows by Morris & Co. including Burne Jones and Rossetti. Wall paintings. Mosaic reredos. Minchenden Oak  - ancient pollarded oak more than 800 years old.

properties.name: Parish Church of St Anne
properties.description: Grade II* listed, originally built as a chapel under the patronage of Queen Anne in 1714 and subsequently enlarged. Many notable memorials including to scientist William Jackson Hooker and tombs of Thomas Gainsborough and Johan Zoffany.

properties.name: Canada Water Library
properties.description: A civic centrepiece for the regeneration of the area around Canada Water. Its inverted pyramid form is an innovative response to providing an efficient single large library floor on a smaller footprint site.

properties.name: The Ice House Quarter (featuring the Granary, Malthouse & Boathouse)
properties.description: Home to the Granary and Malthouse, originally built for Randalls Malt Roasters c1860. The restored buildings include a Victorian Granary and adjacent Malthouse located on the River Roding/ Barking Creek.

properties.name: Roca London Gallery
properties.description: A unique space where water acts as the architectural theme - offering an innovative and interactive experience with Roca, the global bathroom brand.

properties.name: Southwark Integrated Waste Management Facility
properties.description: One of Europe's most advanced recycling facilities, comprising many sustainable features including grey water, solar panels and a green roof. Designed for the purpose of turning waste into a resource.

properties.name: Cody Dock
properties.description: One of London's most exciting creative spaces, Cody Dock provides a gateway to the Lea River Park and is home to a gallery, gardens, cafe & bar that make this the perfect pit stop for exploring The Line Sculpture trail and Lower Lea River.

properties.name: The Clockworks
properties.description: Internationally pre-eminent museum and integral workshops devoted to electrical timekeeping and the distribution of accurate time (1840-1970). Practical education and conservation in action.

properties.name: Salters' Hall
properties.description: A rare example of a Brutalist Livery Hall which underwent extensive refurbishment in 2016. New Pavilion, exhibition and archive space and garden.

properties.name: Darbishire Place (Peabody Whitechapel Estate)
properties.description: New block of 13 homes which completes an ensemble of six housing blocks surrounding an internal courtyard.The façade complements the existing Victorian buildings by Henry Astley Darbishire. RIBA Award Winner & Stirling Prize shortlist 2015

properties.name: St Mary Magdalene
properties.description: A historic living parish church, progressively shaped from the Tudor to the Edwardian period. St Mary's has recently undergone a major refurbishment and the newly restored windows recapture the original airiness of the C18 nave.

properties.name: The Wheelhouse
properties.description: Listed building with unique 7-spoke Victorian waterwheel, the only daily working example in South London, originally used by Liberty's for rinsing printed silk, and now the home of a craft pottery and art studio.

properties.name: St Pancras Chambers and Clock Tower
properties.description: Former Midland Grand Hotel, now St Pancras Renaissance Hotel and Chambers apartments. Includes hotel lobby and clock tower.

properties.name: University of Greenwich, Stockwell Street
properties.description: The building features a limestone exterior designed to 'complement but not mimic' the surrounding historical architecture, whilst behind the façade is a 4-storey composition of steel, glass and exposed concrete.

properties.name: Brentford Canal Toll House and Gauging Lock
properties.description: Single-storey canal toll house (1911) where tolls were collected for passing through the lock. Grand Junction Canal connected the Thames at Brentford to the Industrial Midlands in 1794 at the height of the industrial revolution.

properties.name: Burntwood School
properties.description: Striking precast concrete-clad buildings and refurbishment of Leslie Martin-designed pool and assembly hall, with a new landscape plan for the school's original 1950s Modernist educational campus. Stirling Prize winner 2015.

properties.name: ROOM by Antony Gormley
properties.description: A monumental, inhabitable sculpture placed on a wing of the listed façade of The Beaumont Hotel. The interior, a bedroom, is as important as its exterior: a giant crouching cuboid figure based on the artist's body.

properties.name: German Historical Institute
properties.description: This Grade II* listed building includes an Adam-style ceiling on the 1st floor and a beautiful staircase with wrought-iron balustrade. Once home to the Pharmaceutical Society of Great Britain, it now houses an historical research institute.

properties.name: The Library at Willesden Green
properties.description: A modern 4-storey building incorporating the much-loved Victorian library. The galleries and feature walls display exhibitions and contemporary art and a dramatic central atrium provides natural ventilation and daylight throughout.

properties.name: Modernism in Metroland
properties.description: A walking tour of Stanmore's Art Deco and modernist homes, from the birth of Metroland to the post-war era.

properties.name: Mount Pleasant Villas
properties.description:
A contemporary remodelling of a Victorian terraced property with new features, fittings and materials
Architect-designed for open-plan family life
Space and daylight
Wrap-around rear extension relating to the garden
Conservation Area

properties.name: Waterloo City Farm
properties.description: Feilden Fowles is situated within a walled garden on a discreet corner of Waterloo City Farm. Feilden Fowles designed the farm and its office and educational spaces, which is run by two charities: Jamie’s Farm and the Oasis Community Hub.

properties.name: The Bower
properties.description: Extending AHMM’s involvement in the regeneration of the Old Street area, The Bower reinvents a collection of underperforming buildings into a coherent mix of workspace, ground floor retail/restaurants and a new public realm.

properties.name: Kaymet Factory
properties.description: The operational factory of Kaymet, a maker of trays and trolleys since 1947. A hidden 1950s building with a small yard, originally a printing works. It is brick built, with clear-storey glazing and tubular truss north-light main shed roof.

properties.name: Moravian Close
properties.description: A former stable yard of Sir Thomas More's Chelsea estate, now an 18C Chapel, other buildings, and burial ground. Parts of the enclosing walls are Tudor in origin. Ernest and Mary Gillick enhanced the grounds in the 20C.

properties.name: Phoenix Gardens Community Building
properties.description: The first purpose-built new-build community centre to be built in the heart of Soho for generations, located within the renowned Phoenix Gardens.

properties.name: Goldfinger, Trellick Tower
properties.description: Goldfinger is a social enterprise situated at the foot of the Grade II listed Trellick Tower. We craft bespoke furniture from reclaimed and sustainable materials, with a teaching academy for the local community.

properties.name: Turning Earth Ceramics E10
properties.description: Ceramics centre for the Lee Valley, covering the entire top floor of an old hardware factory. Three rooms, providing just over 8000 sq ft of floor space; the main room is capped by its original saw-tooth glass roof feature.

properties.name: 6 Wood Lane
properties.description: A double-height ark floats above a masonry base & entrance footbridge.  Off the elevated living area a smokers' balcony overlooks the lush garden below. Above, semi circular terrace and winter garden nestles within the wooded surrounds.

properties.name: HG Wells' Bromley - in his own words
properties.description: A virtual walk around the streetscapes that the young Herbert George Wells knew when he was growing up, experiencing the built environment that would later shape his novels.

properties.name: Caledonian Park: Park Walking Tour
properties.description: Tour of the park and local area, discover how Copenhagen Fields became Caledonian Park and how diplomacy gave way to debauchery and agitation and then butchery and commerce.

properties.name: St Mary The Virgin Wanstead
properties.description: One of the finest examples of Georgian architecture. It has been hardly altered since built. The church is a rectangular building of Portland stone, with a projecting chancel. Two external walls were restored in 2019. Grade I listed

properties.name: Chats Palace
properties.description: Homerton Library (Chats Palace) is one of the UK's 660 Carnegie libraries. Designed for “betterment of the people of the East End"  its glass roof, leaded lights, marble floor and pillared frontage testify to the architect's eye for detail.

properties.name: Page High Estate
properties.description: Page High is a hidden jewel of post-war London social housing, a 92-home rooftop village in Wood Green. High above the hue and cry of the High Road, Page High (Good Design in Housing award, 1976) is a model for social housing today.

properties.name: Royal Pharmaceutical Society Museum
properties.description: The RPS museum collections cover all aspects of British pharmacy history, from the 1400s up to the present day. The library's early printed collection includes pharmaceutical texts dating back to 1485.

properties.name: Hornchurch House
properties.description: Newly built contemporary homes designed to be sensitive to their surroundings.

properties.name: Polish Social and Cultural Association
properties.description: Built 1971-74 in brutalist style. The largest Polish centre in Western Europe, it contains a theatre, the Polish Library, the Polish University Abroad, a Joseph Conrad collection, Jazz Café, art gallery and art collection on public display.

properties.name: Aga Khan Centre
properties.description: The Aga Khan Centre, designed by Pritzker prize winning architect Fumihiko Maki, houses the UK institutions of the Aga Khan Development Network. A unique feature are its six gardens inspired by different regions of the Muslim world.

properties.name: Blackbook Winery
properties.description: Blackbook Winery is in a converted Victorian railway arch.  It is open plan, with all equipment required to process, ferment and age wine on site – press, tanks, barrels etc.  Our grapes come from English growers within 2 hours of London.

properties.name: KnoxBhavan Studio
properties.description: Every square inch of this former stationery shop has been maximised in its transformation into an innovative new studio for Knox Bhavan Architects. The studio is dedicated to the idea that workplace environment directly affects wellbeing.

properties.name: Hanwell Community Centre
properties.description: Victorian Grade II listed former Central London District School, known as the 'Cuckoo Schools', was 'home' to up to 1500 pauper children from inner London from 1857-1933.

properties.name: Enfield Brewery
properties.description: A modern open-plan building that houses fully-functioning and impressive brew house equipment. The exterior looks like a clean modern warehouse style building but the interior is updated with industrial equipment.

properties.name: Embassy of the Republic of Poland
properties.description: Georgian townhouse built by Robert and James Adam in the years 1776-1780 is a fine example of the Adam style of Neoclassical interior design. Seat of the Polish Embassy in London since 1921, it also houses a collection of Polish artworks.

properties.name: Gasholder Park
properties.description: Gasholder Park is a tranquil public space set within a carefully restored guide frame of a Victorian gasholder in the heart of King's Cross. The pavilion frames a central garden with a stunning mirror-polished stainless steel colonnade.

properties.name: The Department Store
properties.description: The Department Store is an award winning refurbishment of a dilapidated Edwardian building in Brixton, completed by Squire and Partners in 2017. The design was informed by the layers of history and existing fabric of the heritage building.

properties.name: St Alphege Church, Edmonton
properties.description: The Church of St Alphege is Grade II listed, combining modernist Scandinavian and traditional ecclesiastical forms with good-quality sculptural enrichment; graceful, lofty interiors, with subtle detailing applied consistently throughout.

properties.name: St. Margaret's House
properties.description: St. Margaret's House is a group of buildings centred around a 3-storey Georgian terrace. Victorian additions were made in the building of a Chapel (consecrated 1904) and Mulberry Rooms. The buildings host several community projects.

properties.name: Kingston Historic walk
properties.description:
We are  running our usual guided walking tours around historic Kingston this year with reduced numbers. The tour will be the same but fewer numbers will make it safer for all.
Our guided tours are informative, interesting and fun.

properties.name: Alton Estate
properties.description: Alton Estate is renowned for its mix of high-rise Le Corbusian architecture in Alton West & its low-rise Scandinavian approach to modernism in Alton East. Designed by the London County Council  architects they completed in 1959.

properties.name: St John the Evangelist, Kingston upon Thames
properties.description: The church is a large victorian building with an interesting beautiful interior. The foundation stone was laid in 1871 by Bishop Samuel Wilberforce, son of the anti-slavery campaigner, William.

properties.name: Putting the Park in Wembley Park: an exclusive preview of Wembley Park's emerging Union Park and botanical tour of the neighbourhood's green spaces.
properties.description: Quintain, the award-winning team behind the £3bn regeneration of Wembley Park, will host a series of guided tours of Wembley Park's emerging 7-acre Union Park and other new green spaces across the neighbourhood.

properties.name: Secret Belgravia
properties.description: A peaceful area of Central London that began as 100 acres of marshy land, and became homes to the royal, rich and famous, and of course scandal and intrigue. A beautiful area of London with so many secrets.

properties.name: Olympic Legacy Masterplan
properties.description: London’s 2012 Games provided a catalyst for regeneration in the Lower Lea Valley. Guided by the Legacy Masterplan, thousands of new homes and jobs are now being created, stitching together existing communities across the former floodplain.

properties.name: St Michael and All Angels Church
properties.description: James Maltby Bignall (1827-1885) worked in the practice of Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect of St Pancras Station. The style of St Michael's is late Gothic Revival, in its size and height reminiscent of Northern European churches.

properties.name: St Luke's, Wimbledon Park
properties.description: Architecturally consists of a nave with a gallery at the west end, chancel, north and south aisles. a chapel and south transept with a tower to the north. Three stained glass windows.

properties.name: The City Churches: The Priory Church of St Bartholomew the Great
properties.description: The oldest surviving church in the City of London founded in 1123. Originally part of an Augustinian Priory the church survived the Great Fire and the Blitz.

properties.name: Streatham Space Project
properties.description: A neighborhood theatre, music, comedy venue using cultural events to bring people together. We pride ourselves on being a welcoming space celebrating everyone's creativity from children to emerging producers to experienced artists.

properties.name: Millennium Mills
properties.description: Built in the early 20C by flour company Spillers, the Art Deco landmark has stood vacant since the decline of the docks as a working port in the 1980s.

properties.name: Centre Building: London School of Economics
properties.description: Completed in May 2019, LSE's Centre Building is a state of the art flexible and highly sustainable academic and teaching building, designed by renowned architects Roger Stirk Harbour + Partners.

properties.name: The Royal Bell
properties.description: The Royal Bell is a Grade II listed hotel that has lain empty for over ten years. Designed by Ernest Newton in 1898, it was one of three coaching inns in Bromley and an important centre of Victorian and Edwardian culture.

properties.name: Bethlehem Chapel
properties.description: An independent Calvinistic chapel on the east side of Church Terrace in Richmond, London. Built in 1797, the small 1-storey stuccoed building is Grade II* listed. It still has its original galleried interior with pews and pulpit.

properties.name: Van Gogh House London
properties.description: The carefully renovated Van Gogh House seeks to share its story and inspire a new generation of artists through Van Gogh’s London story. The house curates a dynamic programme of events anchored in the artist’s practice and local heritage.

properties.name: Greenwich Pumping Station
properties.description: The pumping station was built in 1864 by Sir Joseph Bazalgette chief engineer at the Metropolitan Board of Works. The site has a total of four Grade II listed heritage assets including the pumping stations with East and West Beam Engines.

properties.name: Heath Robinson Museum
properties.description: This NLHF supported, accredited, purpose-built museum in Pinner Memorial Park displays a collection of Heath Robinson’s work. It includes permanent & temporary exhibition galleries, activity space & shop. It was designed by ZMMA.

properties.name: Ss Peter & Paul Church
properties.description:
Nave (1844) by Lewis Vulliamy, chancel (1903) by Sir Arthur Blomfield. Stained glass windows by Christopher Webb and 
by Clayton & Bell. Norman font brought from the Old Church. Grade II* listed.

properties.name: Workable
properties.description: Situated within the Rogers Stirk Harbour + Partners designed buildings at IQL, Workable is a new approach to flexible working in Stratford that combines panoramic views over London with stylish interior design.

properties.name: Clitterhouse Farm
properties.description: Our Yard at Clitterhouse Farm is a grassroots project working to protect historic Victorian farm outbuildings and transform the entire site into a vibrant and sustainable community hub. Shortlisted for the Open City Stewardship Awards 2021.

properties.name: New Museum of London, West Smithfield
properties.description: The Museum of London is creating a new museum in the derelict General Market and adjacent post-war Poultry Market. For the first time in 20 years we are inviting the public to explore these spaces in historic and creative Smithfield.

properties.name: The Royal Parks Kiosks
properties.description: A public realm enhancement project across London's Central Royal Parks, including a new landmark café overlooking The Serpentine Lake and nine sculptural "handcrafted" refreshment kiosks.

properties.name: Bluebell Centre, Perivale Wood Nature Reserve
properties.description: The low carbon building is a straw bale construction built on compacted tyres with a cedar roof.  In the Perivale Nature Reserve owned by the Selborne Society it is used for society meeting and as an education centre for adults and schools.

properties.name: Trevithick House
properties.description: Pre war social housing flats, red brick, Georgian sash windows, playground, allotments and washing lines outside.

properties.name: Highgate Junior School
properties.description: Ceramic flooring, interrupted with colourful marble patterns to reflect the school's passion for natural sciences, gives a sense of contemporary grandeur, complemented by seventeen inspired sculptures and reliefs in and around the school.

properties.name: Croydon Minster
properties.description: Medieval style church rebuilt by Sir George Gilbert Scott after 1867 fire. Tower & south porch are 15C. Large nave with open timber-work roof leads to chancel dominated by superb stained glass window & rich alabaster reredos.

properties.name: Hampstead Parish Church (St John-at-Hampstead)
properties.description: The parish church is a focal point at the end of a row of attractive Georgian terraced houses.  The chapel-like exterior is deceiving and the beautiful interior with its high domed ceilings and beautiful stained glass windows is a surprise.

properties.name: Museum of Neoliberalism
properties.description: The museum is situated in a shopfront in Leegate Shopping Centre, which has been described by the Evening Standard as "the worst shopping precinct in the country."

properties.name: Bloom Clerkenwell
properties.description: Bloom Clerkenwell is a wellness focused, new office for developer HB Reavis. With roof terraces, an in-house gym and retail, it is situated over the new  Farringdon Crossrail station and has outstanding links with the city and beyond.

properties.name: Carreducker at 50 Chocolate Studios
properties.description:
A Victorian chocolate factory conversion with exposed girders, brickwork and Crittal-style windows. 

No 50 was transformed from a flat into a traditional, bespoke shoemaking workshop, showroom and shoe & leather craft training school.

properties.name: The Mildmay Club
properties.description: A rare example of a large purpose built metropolitan working men’s club with over 100 years of history. A once dignified building, revival Queen Anne style in the late-Victorian period, Grade II listed in 2019.

properties.name: The Cartoon Museum
properties.description: Underground museum. Interior design by Sam Jacobs Studio. Design concept influenced by cartoon and comic narrative techniques.

properties.name: St Benet Fink Church
properties.description: J S Alder's most complete and unaltered church, at the church's consecration in 1912 it was referred to as 'the little Cathedral' thanks to its light and airy Gothic design.

properties.name: Streatham Pumping Station
properties.description: In 1894 the Streatham Pumping station was built by the Southwark and Vauxhall Water Company, to serve the rapidly expanding suburb of Streatham.

properties.name: Bromley Little Theatre
properties.description: Bromley Little Theatre (BLT) has an 113-seat auditorium that was originally a Victorian bakery and stables built in 1888. The  first production was in December 1937. Please wear masks in the building and observe social distancing.

properties.name: Poplar Works
properties.description: A row of 80 semi derelict garages, has been converted and extended with a timber structure first floor, to provide a fashion hub, with public cafe, manufacturing space, start-up studios, education facility, and business units.

properties.name: Alderman Jones House
properties.description: Becontree Estate two storey cottage house with garden located on a banjo.

properties.name: 1 Finsbury Avenue
properties.description: 1 Finsbury Avenue is a Grade II listed building constructed in the early 1980s by Arup Associates (Peter Foggo). As the first building in the Broadgate development it was significant in defining the speculative office typology in London.

properties.name: House on the End
properties.description: Replacing unused garages, this end-of-terrace, infill site development is a contemporary reinterpretation of the neighbouring terraces, complementing the streetscape and adding a House on the End.

properties.name: Brockley's Historic Mews
properties.description: Brockley Conservation Area's quirky mews are a mixture of leafy lanes and industrial units, with Victorian and interesting modern architecture existing in harmony. The cherished public right of way  allows community contact with nature.

properties.name: Yorkton Workshops
properties.description: Pearson Lloyd have transformed a series of dilapidated workshop buildings into a new home for the studio. Original features have been retained and, wherever possible, the building’s constituent materials have been reused and recycled.

properties.name: Exploring Spring Grove Isleworth
properties.description: Centred on Spring Grove House, once Sir Joseph Banks home the 1850s vision was for John Taylor Jnr designed grand villas.  Today's  wider architecture includes a former college by John Norton & P Massey plus quirky arts & crafts properties.

properties.name: Walk in Brookmill Park
properties.description: Explore this little known park encompassing riverbanks along the tidal Ravensbourne, an old railway embankment, magnificent plane, lime and beech trees, pond, formal area, view of architect David Adjaye's Stephen Lawrence Centre.

properties.name: Reliance Arcade
properties.description: Reliance Arcade is a Grade II Listed covered market in Brixton, London.  The Arcade was constructed in the 1920s and is home to 40 small retail units catering largely to local African-Caribbean communities.

properties.name: Self-Guided Bexley Itinerary, by Open House
properties.description: This self-guided walking itinerary has been created by the Open House team to explore exterior architecture in Bexley.

properties.name: Brockley 3 Peaks Walk
properties.description: A circular 5 mile walk, mainly through parkland with beautiful views across London from the 3 peaks – Hilly Fields, Blythe Hill Fields and One Tree Hill.  The walk is easy to moderately difficult. One Tree Hill is not wheelchair friendly.

properties.name: Christ Church
properties.description: The church is designed in the Gothic style, with a semicircular barrel-vaulted ceiling, a highly carved chancel screen and magnificent stained glass windows, notably the large West window, depicting Christ the King enthroned in heaven.

properties.name: Lansbury Lawrence Primary School
properties.description: Lansbury Lawrence (formally Susan Lawrence and Elizabeth Lansbury) opened in the 1951 Festival of Britain as a showpiece of the Live Architecture exhibition in the Lansbury Estate. An interesting mid-century design with original features.

properties.name: St Matthias
properties.description: St Matthias' spire is easily visible as you approach Richmond Gate (Richmond Park). It is a Grade 2 listed church built between 1858-1862 with additions in 1884 & 1915. It was remodelled in the 1970s to provide both sacred & social space.

properties.name: Rochester Square
properties.description: A half-acre private square in the heart of Camden, dates to 1840s and became a community garden and ceramics workshop since 2016. This year Rochester Square is hosting Foodscape, an urban farm on the site to grow and harvest vegetables.

properties.name: Cool East London Heats Up: Arts Under Pressure
properties.description: In post-Olympic E. London, Hackney Wick had Europe's densest concentration of artists. Now studios & arts spaces struggle to survive gentrification. On these walks we'll visit key cultural locations, meeting those trying to preserve them.

properties.name: GARDEN OF EARTHLY DELIGHTS🌱🐝🍅🦋
properties.description: The Garden of Earthly Delights is a community garden and a "meanwhile" space to raise awareness of empty spaces in the city, grow food for the local community and increase biodiversity. We hold workshops and events to which all are welcome.

properties.name: The Library House
properties.description: Designed by award-winning Macdonald Wright Architects and built in 2020, this two bed, two floor terraced home combines exceptional thermal efficiency, a solar array, exquisitely crafted materials and a secluded walled garden to the rear.

properties.name: The Camera Club
properties.description: Victorian building renovated in 1990 into a photographic gallery, studio and darkrooms to house one of the world's oldest photographic societies.

properties.name: Culture at risk: Crystal Palace Park – a tour with a London Blue Badge Tourist Guide
properties.description:
Explore the world's first dinosaur models hidden in a south London park. The 30 Grade I listed, life-size statues of dinosaurs and other extinct animals at Crystal Palace Park have thrilled
visitors for 166 years. Tour is kids friendly.

properties.name: Wharf Road
properties.description: Designed by architects Pollard Thomas Edwards, the £50m scheme delivered 98 new homes. 80 per cent of the homes are affordable including 64 for social rent. Wharf Road is set around two new communal gardens that face Regents canal.

properties.name: Lanterna, Fish Island Village
properties.description: Designed by Lyndon Goode Architects, Lanterna acts as a gateway to our Fish Island Village development with Hill and was shortlisted for a prestigious Royal Institute of British Architects (RIBA) London Award for architectural excellence.

properties.name: Cromwell Place
properties.description: A first of its kind global arts destination and Membership organisation, Cromwell Place is located in five Grade II Listed townhouses in South Kensington. Home to some of the world’s most exciting art businesses with a range in specialties.

properties.name: Southwark Pupil Referral Unit
properties.description: The Southwark Pupil Referral Unit is a new school for 11-14 year olds who have been excluded from mainstream schools or are at risk of exclusion. The aim is to reintegrate these students into mainstream education.

properties.name: UCL Pearl
properties.description: UCL PEARL is a brand new building designed to be a laboratory that can "house the world" so that we can create different environments from around the world for experiments about people and the environment around them.

properties.name: Birbeck College 373 Euston Road
properties.description: The refurbishment and roof extension of 7-storey building at 373 Euston Road to accommodates a 180-person lecture theatre, high-quality classrooms, as well as formal and informal co-learning spaces.

properties.name: Granary Square Pavilion
properties.description: Granary Square Pavilion is a pavilion incorporating a retail unit, public WCs and public access lift. The pavilion has a decorative cast iron façade that extends up to form a balustrade to Granary Square.

properties.name: Flow Gallery
properties.description: The interior of the building was redesigned in 2014 by John Pardey  to combine a craft gallery with a live work space for the gallery owner. Inspired by Kettle's Yard Flow space exhibits ceramics, glass, wood, textiles and jewellery.

properties.name: Hampstead House
properties.description: Open City presents the film premier of Hampstead House, a renovation of a large Victorian property in Hampstead creating a luxurious and sophisticated family home.

properties.name: Sands End Arts and Community Centre
properties.description: Designed to have a low environmental impact, the new community centre for the London Borough of H&F is a light & airy multi-purpose  scheme providing spaces for art exhibitions & community events with an ancillary café & dance studio.

properties.name: The Sponge
properties.description: An imaginative solution to today's contrasting needs of open spaces and privacy. A large open plan ground floor is carved by joinery items and a wooden slatted box leading to the basement. Natural light filters through the whole house.

properties.name: Structuralist House
properties.description: The project involved the extension and internal reconfiguration of a Victorian mid-terrace house in north London. The design of the four indoor and outdoor levels of the ground floor promotes interactions between inhabitants and visitors.

properties.name: Twofold House
properties.description: Large, openable glass-to-glass sliding doors sit seemingly precariously underneath a massive cantilever and a facetted roof rises up to meet a skylight at the highest point of this imposing extension in the Woodgrange Conservation Area.

properties.name: National Youth Theatre
properties.description: Completed in Summer 2021, the National Youth Theatre has been redeveloped to double its capacity for studio space and was designed with young people, for young people. Recipient of the Mayor of London's Good Growth Fund.

properties.name: Bookend House
properties.description: A modest modern timber extension and refurbishment rationalizing internal spaces and adding an external staircase to connect outdoor spaces, located within the Stroud Green Conservation Area.

properties.name: Case Study Terrace
properties.description: Complete refurbishment of a modern terraced house. This house incorporates a galleried top-floor office space that overlooks a double-height, open-plan kitchen, living and dining space, with sleeping accomodation on the ground floor.

properties.name: Kimber House
properties.description: Rear extension with internal reconfiguration of ground floor, internalisation of garage to create new living space.

properties.name: Wallington Library
properties.description: Wallington library is the oldest library in Sutton borough, built in 1936. Designed by Robert Atkinson in the Neo-Georgian style, it bears the hallmarks of Art Decco design that was typical of the period.

properties.name: Ebury Edge
properties.description: Ebury Edge is a colourful temporary development, providing residents with a continuous community space as the Ebury Bridge Estate is re-developed in phases, together with affordable workspaces and a café.

properties.name: The Old Library - Acton High Street
properties.description: The red-brick property has an ornate façade facing Acton High Street.  It consists of two storeys with part third storey and is one of the historic civic buildings known as the Redbrick Quarter because of their distinctive appearance.

properties.name: Hinde Street Methodist Church
properties.description:
The chapel building is the second on the site, dating from 1887, and the most impressive of the designs of Weslyan Methodist architect, James Weir.
The interior is very attractive,  with a gallery around three sides and a high pulpit.

properties.name: St Barnabas' Church and Mission Hall
properties.description: Early 20th C Grade II* listed church designed by CH Reilly. Byzantine in structure but prefiguring Modernism in its aesthetic, Nairn judged it “the best church of its date in London”, Reilly “the building I should like to be remembered by”.

properties.name: Hyde Park Chapel
properties.description: The four-story Church façade and prominent seven-story tower is covered in Portland stone and highlighted by a golden steeple. The interior features the Christus statue and a large mural of the resurrected Jesus Christ.

properties.name: Holy Trinity Church in Bow
properties.description: Holy Trinity Bow, a Grade C listed Church and graveyard built between 1834 and 1841 lies within the Tredegar Square Conservation Area on a site gifted by the developer of Tredegar Square, Sir Charles Morgan.

properties.name: Kingston Edible Forest 2100
properties.description: A mixed orchard of mostly perennial fruit and vegetables in a natural style to create a woodland and a delightful oasis.

properties.name: St Bride's Church, Fleet Street
properties.description: Wren designed building of 1675, interior lost in blitz of 1940, reopened 1957 with 'Wren inspired' interior

properties.name: Core Kensington
properties.description: A Pilates studio like no other. The design combines functionality with creative and beautiful solutions. Influenced by the Norwegian-Mexican background of the owners, full of bespoke elements and details. The result is warm and minimal.

properties.name: Walter Segal buildings tour
properties.description:
Talk on the method of Walter Segal System, aimed at people interested in using this building method.
Tour of Walters Way, then to a local charity (AFRIL) community/volunteer build on allotments a few mins walk away.
Approx 1 hour.

properties.name: The Musical Museum
properties.description: The current building was specially designed for the Musical Museum, and was opened in June 2008.  In addition to the instrument galleries and roll library, the Museum contains a workshop, concert hall, and a café with views of the river.

properties.name: St John at Hackney Church
properties.description: St John at Hackney Church is the iconic Anglican parish church of Hackney, and has been a centre of Christian worship in the borough Since 1275. The present church was completed in 1792, with a major restoration completed in 2020.

properties.name: RC Church of St Mellitus (St Mellitus Organ Restoration Project)
properties.description: A grandiose neo-classical building with impressive interior built in 1870-1, formerly New Court Congregational church and home to the Hunter pipe organ, built in memory of local WW1 soldiers and recently restored with Lottery funding.

properties.name: White City in the 21st Century
properties.description: External walking tour of the White City redevelopment. Includes new build shopping and housing.  Imperial College White City Campus and the reuse of the BBC Television Centre and Media Village. This is a major redevlopment of the area

properties.name: Boston Manor House and Park Walks
properties.description:
Visitors will be shown around Boston Manor Park on short walks led by volunteers, focusing on the History of Boston Manor House and area.
The House is closed as part of a 5 year redevelopment project, re-opening early 2022.

properties.name: Brook Green
properties.description: We will explore a delightful oasis with Georgian houses, a Victorian church and a public girls’ school. The original brook still flows under the green. Brook Green has been home to actors,  artists' studios and a major national charity.

properties.name: Battersea's Hidden Parks
properties.description: Walking tour introducing nine smaller local parks and public gardens, and revealing their history. Led by Clare Graham, Chair of the Society's Open Spaces Committee and author of 'Discovering Battersea's Open Spaces: a walking guide'.

properties.name: The Old Stables
properties.description: Originally built as horses stables next to the Grand union Canal for a local brewery, it has been used to store barrage balloons and  various industrial uses over the years, currently used as an artist studio.

properties.name: Dorchester House
properties.description: A Grade II listed Art Deco Villa set in landscaped gardens with a spectacular Onyx bathroom, a host of original detailing and a grand  entrance hallway. Designed by Kemp & Tasker who are best known for Odeon cinemas throughout London.

properties.name: Wennington Parish Church of St Mary and St Peter
properties.description: Grade II listed Norman church dating from as early as 1190 and as late as 1248.

properties.name: Creative Mile: Brentford Art Trail
properties.description: A celebration of Brentford's creativity, its industrial past, and it's riverside communities, with artist studios and pop-up exhibitions spread across 8 venues along a one-mile walking route running from Kew Bridge down to Johnson's Island.

properties.name: A River's Tale. A guided walk along the Thames Path
properties.description: For about an hour and a half we will walk along the Thames Path from Millennium Bridge  finishing at the old Billingsgate Fish Market along the way learning of the prosperity, power, prestige and plague this great river has brought us

properties.name: Ripple Greenway and the Lost Words Art Trail
properties.description:
Ripple Greenway is a beautiful 14-acre linear park and art trail.  Home to Katy Hallett’s steel sculptures, inspired by Robert Macfarlane’s and Jackie Morris’ The Lost Words.
Wooden play and exercise equipment, picnic tables and benches.

properties.name: Jubilee Market
properties.description: The Jubilee Hall, which houses the Jubilee Market, was built in 1904 in the heart of Covent Garden and gained Grade 2 listed status in 1980. The market was officially re opened after renovation by Queen Elizabeth II in 1987.

properties.name: East Dulwich Extension
properties.description: A rear and side brickwork extension with pitched zinc roof with sliding doors and glazed courtyard separating new family kitchen from main house.  A simple tonal palette of pale brick, clay pavers and bespoke plywood cabinetry.

properties.name: Self-guided Architecture Walk - Upper Richmond Road westwards
